messages.text: For today’s 7.1 lab, if you try to run `spark-submit` locally in your Mac (like me) after installed java, scala, spark, etc, do not run that command under your `DSCI6007/7.1 fancy name with spaces/lab/my_awesome.py` folder. Instead, copy your `my_awesome.py` to a clean folder that do not have space in the file path. Otherwise you have “file not found” error for some reason…
I’ll send out a write-up of the demo I did in class with tomorrow’s solution

These are the learning objectives for this course:

- Install and run a Linux virtual machine locally and in the cloud
- Utilize *NIX command line tools to manipulate and analyze data
- Deploy and manipulate data and working code in the cloud
- Identify embarrassingly parallelizable tasks and parallelize them
- Describe and apply the MapReduce algorithm
- Write complex SQL queries
- Design a database that conforms to the third normal form (3NF)
- Describe and apply Spark’s DataFrame abstraction
- Perform machine learning on a cluster
- Analyze streaming data “real-time”
- Apply probabilistic data structures to handle high volume/velocity data
- Build an end-to-end distributed data-pipeline

Of these, the first five have been assessed through labs. The next four (SQL,  3NF, Spark’s DataFrame, and ML) have been assigned but have not yet been graded. The next two will be assessed this week. The last one is ongoing.
The mastery tracker is generous, taking the highest score available for each category and not penalizing for lateness. As a result, everyone is doing quite well on the first five standards. Hopefully by now everyone has turned in their Spark DataFrame and Spark SQL labs which will contribute to those standards as well. Many of you are behind on your data-pipeline, however, given that your submissions for the 4.4 lab are either missing or incomplete. Hopefully this is corrected in the 6.3 lab (I’m checking now).

attachments.title: There's Just No Getting around It: You're Building a Distributed System - ACM Queue
attachments.text: Building a distributed system requires a methodical approach to requirements.: Distributed systems are difficult to understand, design, build, and operate. They introduce exponentially more variables into a design than a single machine does, making the root cause of an application problem much harder to discover. It should be said that if an application does not have meaningful SLAs (service-level agreements) and can tolerate extended downtime and/or performance degradation, then the barrier to entry is greatly reduced. Most modern applications, however, have an expectation of resiliency from their users, and SLAs are typically measured by "the number of nines" (e.g., 99.9 or 99.99 percent availability per month). Each additional 9 becomes harder and harder to achieve.

messages.text: SQLMagic shows how to simply use a Jupyter notebook to execute SQL directly. That is sufficient for tomorrow’s lab. However, for your final project (and when you are working professionally) you will probably want to pull the data into a DataFrame so you can feed it into `statsmodels` or `sklearn` or `seaborn` or whatever. So the code in SQLPandas will help get you started with that.

:point_up_2::skin-tone-3: I’ve added a couple Jupyter notebooks to the repo to help show how to work with SQL from Jupyter. SQLMagic.ipynb is taking directly from a lesson in the 6002 class I used to teach. SQLPandas.ipynb is just some starter code to show you how to get data from a database into a Pandas DataFrame.

Triadic closure is a concept in social network theory, first suggested by German sociologist Georg Simmel in his 1908 book Soziologie [Sociology: Investigations on the Forms of Sociation]. Triadic closure is the property among three nodes A, B, and C, such that if a strong tie exists between A-B and A-C, there is a weak or strong tie between B-C. This property is too extreme to hold true across very large, complex networks, but it is a useful simplification of reality that can be used to understand and predict networks.

messages.text:
Here's a friendly reminder about the course methodology from the class syllabus.  Note that we're looking to promote ideation and creative thinking.  This can be a significant departure from what you've seen elsewhere, and it will make you significantly stronger in this field

Course Methodology: What Not How

Materials for this course will focus more on what needs to be accomplished, and less on how to accomplish it. That is, you will still need to know how to accomplish these goals, but you may be expected to be more self-reliant on finding and utilizing those materials yourself than you have been in the past. This course promotes ideation, or translating worldly problems into data problems. The power of this tool cannot be underestimated for once we translate a worldly problem into a data problem we move into the realm of Moore's law and our impact becomes exponential. This is a shift from having pre-made exercises common in data science curriculums to having to think critically about your motivating question and the end-to-end implementation of your pipeline.

Being able to teach yourself how to use a new technology is essential to your role as a data scientist. These tools evolve quickly and what is wired today will be tired tomorrow. It is not unknown for a tool to be deprecated in the course of a minimester. To the extent that we do provide instructions on "how", and do our best to keep the content of the course as up-to-date as possible, sometimes links will be dead, instructions will be out dated, and so on. You will have to rely on your colleagues and your ingenuity to figure out what to do.

Update: in light of the above video, it mentions `autocomplete-python` and choosing your local engine but it looks like he skipped the part where you install your local engine. That’s Jedi.

On the topic of atom plugins, `autocomplete-python` works pretty well but be sure to `conda install jedi`.
Keep in mind now with these (particularly with `jedi` and `autocomplete-python`) it matters what conda environment you’re in. Atom will only know about the python libraries in the environment in which you run it. For example, I have `twitter` installed in my `dsci6007` environment but not in my default environment. So if I execute atom by, say, double-clicking on the Atom icon in Applications, `autocomplete-python` won’t know about `twitter`. But if I run it from the command line with my conda environment already activated, it will.
